passages.text: Feeling Like a Rockstar - - ELH Buys Rockstar and Moves Alani to PEP Distribution

Celsius Holdings (CELH, OW- rated, Analyst Focus List) and Pepsico (PEP, N- rated) announced a new agreement this morning that encompasses three key components (details below) for \(\) 585M\(in the form of new preferred shares, increasing PEP ownership from 8.5% to 11.3% on a fully diluted basis (as converted). We attended the initial announcement conference call and also the follow- up call with senior management. Our take on the deal is positive, as it allows CELH to grow its market share in the energy category from \~17% to \~20%+ with control over the marketing, shelf space/displays for three brands (now including Rockstar) at a very attractive valuation when accounting for the points of market share acquired (\~70 to 80% discount to CELH brands). While Rockstar has been underperforming and bleeding market share (more below), it has summed\)\\(250M\) in sales in the last twelve months (already adjusted for the rationalization of SKUs). CELH is planning to rationalize SKUs and better utilize shelf space with the freedom to move some of the Celsius and Alani Nu products into the existing Rockstar shelf space. Most importantly, from Alani Nu's brand standpoint, PEP's distribution will open more doors in fast growing segments, including foodservice, as well as more penetration in convenience and gas station (C&G) channel, a massive white space for Alani Nu, in our view. The Alani Nu brand resonates with women, who now represent \(40\%\) of the energy market and have been the fastest growing cohort in the industry. To our question on the initial call this morning, management sounded very positive about the most recent trends for Alani Nu, in particular its limited edition launches (LTOs), which is consistent with the sales acceleration we saw in the tracked channel data (link) and our monthly deep dive in the Energy Category (link). Management said that the combined deal will be accretive in its first year, but there will be some customary adjustments for the distribution transition, including inventory reserves and write- offs, especially in Q4.

1. Alani Nu brand will move to PEP's Distribution System in the U.S. and Canada, amplifying Alani Nu's reach into foodservice and C&G channels. We believe it will also better align the incentives, as PEP is an indirect shareholder, vs. previous ABI wholesalers. PEP will be responsible for the distribution breakup fees.

2. Expanding CELH's Portfolio to Conventional Energy Drinks. CELH has acquired the Rockstar Energy brand in the U.S. and Canada from PEP, (still about 50% of the market, currently dominated by N-rated Monster, and privately held Red Bull). PepsiCo will continue to own the Rockstar Energy brand internationally.

3. Captaincy of the Energy Shelf with CELH, While PEP Takes Distribution of Three Brands. Celsius Holdings will have full control of the shelf in the energy category for the three brands it now owns. The release noted that CELH will "become PepsiCo's strategic energy lead in the U.S., managing the CELSIUS®.

Alani Nu and Rockstar Energy brands, while Pepsico will lead distribution for the Celsius Holdings portfolio in the U.S. and Canada." The control will be similar to the structure that MNST has with KO and has been a relatively successful partnership post the arbitration process in the past. We broadly agree with the statement on the release that "this agreement leverages the respective strengths of Celsius Holdings and PepsiCo to scale the combined energy drink portfolio with a more unified commercial strategy."

- Deal Economics Seems Attractive to CELH. PepsiCo's ownership in Celsius Holdings increased to \(11.3\%\) from \(8.5\%\) "on an as-converted basis, and PepsiCo will nominate an additional director to serve on Celsius Holdings' board of directors, further strategically aligning both companies for the long term. On a market share basis, the deal allowed CELH to acquire \(\sim 2.5\%\) share of the category at an attractive valuation.
Celsius Holdings (Overweight; Price Target: \(68.00)

We rate Celsius Holdings (CELH) Overweight. We view CELH as well positioned to reaccelerate growth in the coming years as the company moves past idiosyncratic top- line headwinds and benefits from improving consumption trends in the energy drinks category following a slowdown in 2024. Longer- term, we see CELH benefiting from being at the intersection of a number of consumer megatrends (e.g., health & wellness/fitness, functionality/energy, zero sugar, premiumization), which we believe should position the brand for market share gains in the U.S. and internationally as distribution continues to expand. Against this backdrop, we believe CELH shares appear attractively valued following significant earnings revisions and multiple de- rating in 2024.

Our Dec 2026 target price of \(68 is based on a one- third/two- thirds blend of non- alcoholic beverages/fast growing consumer peer sets, embedding 19.7x EV/EBITDA and 34.9x P/E off our CY27 estimates. Our\) 68 Dec 2026 target price implies \(\sim 35\%\) upside potential over the next roughly 17 months.
